No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused to propose to abolish the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted under an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the exemption of the imprisoned Prime Minister, was rejected by the MPs at the second reading of the request for mitigation of the penalties for economic offenses.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of an allegedly adverse treaty with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicts is to be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself calls the ruling a political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised suspicions of the court's bias.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted, from the Criminal Code was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been required to its adoption.
