The menu of a fat-addicted child: It does not have breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all pupils and 5 per cent of all children being overweight.
Current surveys have been shown - obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows once again how important it is for the healthy development of a person, the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more common on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had fries for dinner on the day before the enlightenment campaign under the motto "Obesity is no coincidence".
In families with thickenings, sports are not exactly one of the favorite activities, but this also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent replied that their parents find themselves at least once a week time for active exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4 and 8 have participated in the project. Classes part.
Unhealthy food and lack of movement in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the frighteningly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, cited eating five times a day, in the mode of breakfast-second breakfast-noun-vesper evening bread - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," reads one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families of the students eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast for themselves.
Worst of all, the finding was that in every tenth family, it is not eating breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the cornerstone of healthy daily nutrition.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that unhealthy fries are consumed much more often in the families of overweight children.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, only less than half of their parents do so - namely only 15 percent.
Put together your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to put together their own meal plan from opportunities offered for appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet sodas," is emphasized in the final report on this survey.
At lunch, the main course, pasta won just ahead of poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get proper information.
"In the case of the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the enlightening lecture "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the results of the project stated.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet sodas, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also ticked poultry or fish much more often in the questionnaire than the main course of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
