We stuck and glued ourselves...
With the scissors you must not even touch the shoes, so that you do not damage them.
So you really have to be skillful.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without restrictions.
The mentioned skill is not exactly my strength.
All this was only the fraction of what we heard at the second weekend resume course.
One thing has become clear to me in the meantime - devoting to styling on a professional level is not a breeze.
V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree journey is caused by a series of completely avoidable, dilettante errors to the routine trip to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions to a large extent, but what good is this if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
He promised to move the already year-old game series "Need for Speed" again a piece into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not only one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the fitted passages turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall, the game is diminished by some superfluous errors that have been more or less present in this series for a few years.
So it is actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First, one is introduced to the story whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and into more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't get a moment to get the impression that game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of the graphic does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through snow-covered scenery looks visually very pleasant.
From time to time, atypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you will be surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are quite well installed one after the other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then a personal duel with a single opponent awaits you.
And this is also the case with the police, who want to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (in concrete terms probably only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the matter, because so this element has at least no chance of getting boring - it belongs in the context of the above to the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model is following in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, seen from today's point of view, it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed racing race will continue to do justice to the local driving model quite well, although you could find better ones with the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only arise after a while.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
It is hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you do not know how the car behaves before any impact on any object, then obviously not everything is okay.
Typical example: When narrowly overtaking or passing on oncoming cars, you only "swipe" the other car slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into a skid and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the cart is about to go to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter anything, from an annoying thing it is all.
The restarts are solved like this: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
When you exhaust them, everything starts all over again.
The restarts are therefore more of a tool, in the event that something does not succeed, but you should rather not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart does not even help, so nothing helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
What is very unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, you have to drive through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Elsewhere, you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent passes two oncoming cars in front of you, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken in the same place by the same opponent and again here without regard to the time.
This is the most crazy thing at the end of the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake one here on devil come out.
And when he is already in front of you, he of course takes your view, so that you drive your own car in Klump a few times.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly avoids you the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so action-packed that you almost don’t know where your head is anymore.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilt" is to do with it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car in the course of the races.
You must not overlook the gas stations on the track, because here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have just has is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical journeys, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story also goes the task mode (challenges) - so the races in the individual localities, which you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for the own profile to win, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
To get to the higher driver level, various items must be unlocked: from the car, to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also associated with the online function Autolog, which compares, among other things, the own results achieved with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of another incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the final race of history.
Here you come by car to a subway tunnel (mean reason), where you race in the dark on the rails long (because of me).
On the speedometer, digits between 150 a 200 km/h (my way), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you uncompromisingly to scrap.
In our editorial team we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and sometimes quite dramatically.
However, this applies in particular to the accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The tone reproduction is so far O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a more young audience as wide as possible scale, a soundtrack a lá "from everyone something" was created - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we could have claimed with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared for these mistakes with the power of airport headlights in the eye.
