IBM history: From cheese cutter to space flights
Founded in New York a hundred years ago, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
She took over the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history until the 1980s. Century goes back.
They possessed technologies such as the famous lancing card clocks to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who was the boss of rival company Thomas J. Watson hired to help him manage the company.
This leader even eclipsed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still based today on the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its revenues to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA conduct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, man's famous flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of that time was released in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off in the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet."
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a clever way in areas not even planned, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and city administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which is intended to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM founded a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia - the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters is located in Prague and here is also a top world-class research team that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
