Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the ČSSR at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West at that time only chosen.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
It was a great paradox of those socialist times that it was not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things hadn't gone long.
The so-called. Foreign exchange commitment - the condition for leaving the West - was only granted to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
Most Czechs, therefore, spent their holidays domestically, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and daches - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the obligation to exchange for foreign exchange was lifted to the neighboring Western European countries, which provoked a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a guesthouse at that time.
A typical feature of foreign trips from Czechs at that time was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krona - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our living level and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare for charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had forefrontless payment transactions with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand - thanks to the high demand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to far-flung sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flyed directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On the 17. In November 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely placed our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time and for the first time in their history they gave more than 15 thousand for a single holiday stay including the costs at the holiday resort. CZK per capita.
