Splash in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real treat: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"On the one hand, it is transparent, but on the other hand reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkali-containing water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can enjoy the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton look out over the snow-covered Arlberg - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
From three bowls open upwards, it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not every swimming pool, the pool collector Meder climbed the smell of chlorine into the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it stinks so much like heating oil, which you hardly believe to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to the skin as soon as you glide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a closed-off terrain.
The bathroom, designed in 1902 by the architect Dušan Jurkovic, has since been closed.
When Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds proliferate between the tiles.
