21er Haus in Vienna
The reschedled pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy ending: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and lost.
Now it is being reopened as an exhibition house.
When raving about modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition is an apt and famous example.
Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria’s pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like branch building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna Südbahnhof, rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20. Century opened - the "20s house" it was called.
However, the building was not spatially and technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new start was completed by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a doctoral student in art with a considerable career, among other things, in his youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly enforced the conversion among politicians and preservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship money and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore were to be available, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the implementation, Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an "enormously important place" for him, where he had looked at the exhibitions "almost every weekend."
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and ease when it was transferred to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: The building was "an energy slingshot," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass-fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between the house and street provides the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tailer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema hall is even exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also pleased the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such an architecture "always stands in the wrong place" and still wants to "arouse a real awareness."
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban planning stroke of luck has occurred: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "main station district", with office and residential buildings, is currently being built.
And another stroke of luck will perhaps still occur: The 21er Haus could get reinforcements from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborly location in the Swiss garden.
