Smart crows are spreading in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": but the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: Crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities, residents' complaints about dirt and noise of the animals accumulate.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer available from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian town of Leer.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
Are you looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the particularly protected seed crows: The use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroys the traditional habitats.
The hunting, increasing development and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs are available in Soest, Westphalia, in the northwest, including in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen, and in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project to kill crows in the county had caused negative headlines.
Critics had described the catching of the animals in bird traps and the slaying with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal displacement, the debrising, is of no use," the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer has noted.
Spraying nests with water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Disturbance is only conceivable as an exception at hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away anymore."
Without the surrounding area, the problem in the cities cannot be solved, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of the debris of the animals from sensitive living areas and attracting offers is conceivable in order to resettle them in other places.
"Infotafeln instead of chainsaws", on the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens advocated a completely different approach to the animals: "After all, we can best endure a pimple on the face with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberg crow trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: seed crows not only use aids to get a treat, but even produce their own tools as a tool.
Behavioural scientists from the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds extends.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to collapse a scaffolding with stones in order to get to a moth larva.
Without much training, they determined the size and shape of a stone in order to collapse the platform.
In a second attempt, the smart crows then had to solve a trickier problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had put wire pieces on them.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded in this immediately.
