Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online sponsors of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twisting, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more sensible, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends like in "Likes," text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook's "Datasupernova" is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this page people you don’t usually reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very hard to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and that would never have granted them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, all this falls away - you go straight to them."
Others say the site provides a way to recognize and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their full-throated on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent on this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer students, for example, residential counselors, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you didn't recognize it," Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle told The Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site's data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Lucky Index (which primarily used information that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data treasure trove accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want to or not. In order to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to dispose of your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
"I don't think many users even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles," Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, says of a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she is concerned, it was all about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how many of the information is true in a user profile and in posts.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools that anyone can use.
"There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research has to take care of the social - and a lot of social life still takes place offline."
