Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of the violations in campaign finance, which is related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office regarding his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about cheating at school and at college exams are widely available.
There were incidents in which teachers gave their students the exam answers so that they were good even in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies show, we lie between 10 and 200 times every day.
Many of these lies are considered to be no need lies.
Another study shows strangers lying to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "Uncovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Have you!", unmasking a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been unmasked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stammer, blush and fidget.
From this, however, it must not be concluded that these liars are difficult to detect and expose.
A practiced unsailer of lies can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the assertion, the subtle facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing area of unmasking. And it is clear that unmasking a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to navigate our complex world, especially if hiring or questioning people or negotiations or administration are among our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, arousing their interest and mastering their own emotions. And they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people are more likely to lie than introverts that men are more likely to show up "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "oriented to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less frequently than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that if one person has been exposed as a culprit, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone usually trips with their foot all the time, so they don't wrongly blame him when he's going to trip with his foot during a meeting.
Then watch for accumulations of striking verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of unmasking.
