Climatic adversity put the brakes on the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, Sinaloa will be remembered in the economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and raised high hopes regarding economic growth, is at the government. However, as a result of the climate adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in the millions in agriculture, but also set tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historic reduction of agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a slowing effect on other economic sectors.
According to a Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (ed. Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) report on the effects of the frost was damaged in 582 000 hectares of agricultural land, of which 78.03 percent was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed. Especially the vegetable, corn and chickpea cultivation were affected.
The decline in economic activity until November has caused unemployment in the Mexican state to rise steadily. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid rise in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa. That's 18 969 more people than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in that year is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the politics of public institutions indirectly declares the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is a rise in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in funds by the legislation passed to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for anything else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, particularly in the United States, has declined. This is due on the one hand to the entry problems and on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work here, which raises unemployment," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when taking into account the high proportion of undeclared work. According to INEGI, this includes 60.38 percent of the employees in the country who work without paying into the social insurance funds.
Low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institution) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Authority for Labour and Social Care in Mexico), come to unemployment and undeclared work.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September; this is much less than the general government average, which stands at 7375 pesos.
Decline of ADI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and growing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (state economic authority), the ADI was 630 597 dollars from January to June, which corresponds to a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period in the previous year.
For its part, the Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, which is mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos, which should be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The National Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be identified by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's incapacity for government evident.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico) represented that in 2011 no effort was made to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa this year was really very poor. It has to be hard work to regain the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we have to put in a double effort. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-attended government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López expressed that events, such as the frost at the beginning of the year, made the country's economic development difficult and slowed.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently moving to evoke an economic dynamic that could generate a decent flow of processes, products and services. That's why we're going to close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Entrepreneurs Association of Mexico) in Sinaloa, said that the state had to be persuaded to do more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we observed that work was done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redetermine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot of work to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that puts the government's efforts in better shape.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress on the government.
