The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is coming to fruition"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They were expected to spend more than 20 years, but the band assures that a dream comes true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
That's what the group's bassist and co-founder, Jeff Ament, assured Viva of an exclusive interview last week from Brazil.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 19:30 together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the conversation, the complete transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam is set in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is also a reality for us.
This is just the second time we've played in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I was only on holiday in Costa Rica once. It's such a beautiful country that we'll definitely stay there for a few more days.
It's exciting for us to get our music there.
I'm asking you this because the band's fans are completely devoted. You will experience the days before the concert intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put some pressure out of your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've put on over the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We've played on a couple of huge shows in Sao Paulo and we're hoping they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we feel like playing there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are thrilled by the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends always went surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, about people who love surfing, we learned about it.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the Costa Rica event?
Since we have never played there, we have no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from every album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we will play is not easy.
If we record two or three songs that we have not played for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they could be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think so for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty years of history.
If you look back, do you find it difficult to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I think that none of us imagined to play in a great rock band, and for more than 20 years. It looks like a dream.
We continue to rely on this blessing and think it’s great to be able to make music together now.
We like each other and are excited to bring out music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things could not stand better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to belong to this group of bands.
We're good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every once in a while, a band emerges from a city, but it's already unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on her tour. We're excited to still be friends with all of them and it honors us to be part of that emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I think we are all lucky to still be alive and we also take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't do better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall into this game with huge crowds that love your music.
As long as you think people have come because of the music, that reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has launched without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We never cared anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think of what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It has always been a joy to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why the band chosen for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band best. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. I'm sure it'll be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings him, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who were you influenced by as a bass player?
Of so many+
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk about the bass players I like all afternoon.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I can think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that’s great, because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
Initially, her music was darker, now she's more positive.
Why? Why?
That's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit light. But there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe, which are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
To both of them, tears came to me when I heard Ed play them. They're very dark songs.
I believe that as you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, when you lose a family member or a friend - that affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
Peru:
Fujimori came to the hospital again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his GP informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for violating human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several conditions, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal physician, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish this because he considered him innocent.
He has had four times to undergo tongue cancer and he has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor enumerated.
Fujimori has been at the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía detention centre since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which secretly worked during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official secondment, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will launch their visit from Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region
Mujica meets with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. That will be the culmination of his fully booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the Uruguayan president.
The discussion of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support regarding the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community. That statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and industrialized countries. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double assessment with the South American country.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the concretization of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD). This is what countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
