The organization was created to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the Trinijove social welfare organisation have led to important results: in this quarter of a century, 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported in order to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which over 300 people took part, was taken stock yesterday.
Trinijove was launched in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of training, no work, with drug problems that were threatened by the risk of marginality.
The celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous officials from institutions and institutions that have cooperated with the association during these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions during election campaign times proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the celebrations were attended by the former Socialist Education Minister Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The great hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Sparkasse La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated. But he added that the work done so far is "a good basis."
For the president of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a role model who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in trouble.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it is doing," he explained.
