Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announces details of the plane accident that killed government secretary Francisco Blake and another seven people.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the investigation results about the accident, which killed the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people, indicated that the helicopter with all its intact structure directly bounced against the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before takeoff that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller blades had contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of the personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had come down.
"No aircraft parts were found elsewhere in the search, the mark-up affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Relief Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown by the Estado Mayor Presidencial on the surcharge with cruising speed and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be considered in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In line with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew would have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the start. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds drew up.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds, the crew had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are in agreement. There may not have been a loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Disseminate the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to now indicates that the helicopter had bounced from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggests the helicopter had impacted the ground with its unharmed structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the scene of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest investigation results point to several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter has probably broken.
Some information suggests the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area that went beyond the cordoned-off area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the unharmed aircraft structure had bounced against the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
She Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for childhood and adolescents, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institution of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for childhood and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence," with which the genetic markers are to be found in conjunction with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate degree program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began on the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and has been going on since 8. October will continue on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will continue on the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and will be completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and the role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
