Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, is using polymers to develop modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs that originate from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes if the rainy season at the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico) breaks out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assured that if the laying out and maintenance of the asphalt surface are adequately reduced
In his lecture "Pothles from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalts modified with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic tough-elastic behavior.
Tough-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
"Across the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
The most forces of this road surface are received and distributed, the support layer also requires an appropriate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates the layer and only emerges again with difficulty. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only impaired afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs through appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is observed in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many more research work was still waiting, for example about asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired simply and without the application of high temperatures.
