Last 4. In November, a lopscopist of the investigative unit of the prosecutor's office (CTI) from Cali as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González had volunteered, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he frequently had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin, which is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and foot surfaces.
In the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew he was supposed to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one could be that of the man who had run the oldest guerrilla in the world. That's why he should take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name) with him.
However, when he reached the place where the corpse was located with the most examination, he could not identify it because of his physical appearance, because this did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media, in the least.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer of the area, did not wear glasses and was very much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the corpse's fingerprints to those on the imprint sheet.
He had seen right: It was "Alfonso Cano."
Even the same night, this man, from Puerto Tejada, was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that it was actually the head of the FARC.
In search of traces
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science without an error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery matters and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When arrested, many criminals present false identification papers or they have none.
We take the fingerprints off them and search for them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in a theft, because the thief had supported himself with his hand at this point when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprint removal. But in this case, we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had taken part in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of the fingerprints, murder suspects can also be exonerated or charged.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
The investigation was suspected that a family member might be suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, he is nevertheless associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A Dactyloscopeist of the CTI explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object."
When they appear, a planter or ribbon is used for taking it.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification papers," explained the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything was as it would be portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all gold, which shines, is not all that you touch, a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
