Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill, unlike our French households.
Since the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key role in competitiveness and a demand for industry stability on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a strong increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Polls found that this was a price that the vast majority of French people are just as willing to pay as they show opposition to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to phase out nuclear power, most of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual 6 billion euros in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
