Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies on the basis of a policy subject to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights," as France had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students from the authorities had shaped the newsreels, the interior minister had casually (see Libération of 23. May) announces that France "does not need talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad."
But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a wide-ranging consensus between the right and the left on this issue.
From the right, the tone of Jacques Chirac was struck, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed people, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country," from the left by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 had stated that France "could not absorb all the poverty in the world."
The only difference is in the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared in 2005 from both the right and the left.
From both camps, the immigrants were perceived as a burden to the economy and French society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity that is willing to admit to immigrants.
Francois Hollande limits his programme to banalities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems."
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, can potentially affect the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As the economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present to us in a recent work that summarizes the latest findings regarding immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists regarding the positive influence of the immigrant flood on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Restricting immigration would invalidate growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of the migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the domestic workers, especially the less skilled, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in truth much more complementary than the domestic wage workers, since they focus on occupations in sectors that are unutilised in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract any incentives to domestic wage workers, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not matched to the supply of work.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anesthesisists, so this complementarity also between locals and migrants has a positive effect of immigrant influx on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants brings about a co-involved, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of idea creation and economic growth brought in by the immigrants is beneficial (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
The migrants also contribute net to the social systems, in the European countries on average about 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 contributes on average a net contribution (income minus expenses) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" to start his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
