Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline last Tuesday on the Baltic coast under orchestral sound system and at gourmet buffet, which directly connects Russia and Germany below sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the wheel of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year are to be delivered to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length, which connects the St Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of the French total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line sound on its own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little power: for them, it is now becoming more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to enter Western European markets.
Warsaw, most committed to the debate, was not shy away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Asi-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained an even higher security of supply by advocating for this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of an invalidation of European energy, as the project has struck a breach between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has managed in barely five years to push through its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries that have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technology.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, mine fields dating from the Second World War had to be dodged.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long snake made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from this, as the Swedes were not eager to see a Russian state-owned company settle in a permanent way at the height of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller clarified.
In the event of a leak, the gas located in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with one meter diameter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of locomotion through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about any deformations of the metal on its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have combined their strengths to realize this project.
However, the line guidance remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, here are the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group of companies GDF Suez (each at 9%).
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented out the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, namely on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transported amount of gas fails," Jens Müller clarified.
The financing of the gas transmission construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are sure to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy coastline wooded with pine trees at Lubmin.
The 4.5-meter-high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
